<p><b>How old is the narrator in Foster by Claire Keegan?</b> Keegan divides her novella into 8 chapters that take place over the course of a single summer within rural Ireland. The main character, who serves as the novella's first-person narrator, is a roughly 10-year-old girl who remains nameless throughout.</p>
<p><b>What is the Foster book about?</b> A child is taken by her father to live with relatives on a farm, not knowing when or if she will be brought home again. In the Kinsellas' house, she finds an affection and warmth she has not known and slowly, in their care, begins to blossom.</p>
<p><b>Who are the Kinsellas in Foster?</b> The Kinsellas, John and Edna, have no children of their own and will foster the girl on their small farm in Wexford, toward the southeastern coast of Ireland.</p>
<p><b>What is the setting of the book Foster?</b> “Foster” is a moving short story set in a sweltering summer in Wexford in the early 1980s. With the impending birth of yet another sibling, a young girl is taken to stay with the Kinsellas for the duration of the summer.</p>
<p><b>Where does Claire Keegan live?</b> Her stories have been translated into 12 languages. "Every line seems to be a lesson in the perfect deployment of both style and emotion" Hilary Mantel. A member of Aosdana, Keegan now lives on the Wexford coast.</p>
<p><b>What is Foster's final piece of advice?</b> So here's my final piece of advice: Own the books you read.” This quote takes place in the Postscript, as Foster is encouraging his readers to take ownership of what they read. Here, Foster tells his readers not to apologize for their interpretations.</p>
